  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "A zine is a small, self-published work of text and images, typically reproduced by photocopier or other low-cost means and distributed outside commercial publishing channels. The word is short for \u0026ldquo;magazine\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;fanzine,\u0026rdquo; and the form is defined less by any particular content than by its mode of production: cheap, fast, and controlled by its maker rather than by an editor, publisher, or distributor.\nZines emerged from the amateur press associations and science fiction fan communities of the early-to-mid twentieth century, where enthusiasts circulated mimeographed newsletters and commentary. The term \u0026ldquo;fanzine\u0026rdquo; was coined in the 1940s for these fan-produced publications. By the 1970s and 1980s, punk scenes had adopted and transformed the form: zines like Sniffin\u0026rsquo; Glue and Maximum RocknRoll treated rough layout, visible cut-and-paste, and photocopier artifacts not as limitations but as markers of authenticity and refusal of professional gatekeeping.\n",
